<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-11-13T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-11-13T00:00:00-05:00" n="112" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d112">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">862.852/54</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Honduras</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Erwin</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 861</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Tegucigalpa</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-11-13">November 13,
                                1939</date>.<lb/>[Received November 20.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that I was
                            informed today by Mr. Harold Darlington, British Vice Consul in
                            Tegucigalpa, that it has been reliably reported the German freighter <hi rend="italic">Wesermunde</hi>, at present at Curaçao, West Indies,
                            is negotiating for a change of registry to the Honduran flag. The new
                            name this vessel will take is <hi rend="italic">Chirropo</hi>, according
                            to this report.</p>
                        <p>It is believed that the effort to change to Honduran registry at this
                            time is motivated by the fact that the ship is now in a port controlled
                            by the Dutch and that this step is being taken as protection for the
                            German owners in the event the Netherlands break relations with
                            Germany.</p>
                        <p>Respectfully yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">John D. Erwin</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>